    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5b2c9270-55e7-4bdc-865e-f105edda9757",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a slight, pale-complexioned 10-year-old boy from Brno, Czech Republic, who sits rigidly on the examination chair, hands clasped tightly in his lap. He has dark circles under his eyes and fidgets constantly with the sleeve of his school uniform. He speaks softly and carefully, often pausing mid-sentence as if checking whether his words are correct. During the consultation, {patientName} occasionally presses a hand to his chest, reporting that his heart sometimes \"beats too fast and too hard,\" particularly before school tests. He is visibly sweaty on his palms and forehead even in the cool clinic room.\n\nAt school, {patientName} is described by his teachers as a diligent but overly cautious pupil in the 4th grade. He spends long hours re-checking his homework and worries excessively about upcoming tests, sports days, and even small social interactions with classmates. He has one close friend but avoids group activities for fear of making mistakes. He enjoys building LEGO sets and reading books about dinosaurs in the quiet of his room. His teachers have also noted that he struggles to concentrate during lessons, frequently losing track of instructions or staring blankly before refocusing.\n\n{patientName}'s parents report that he has been complaining of persistent stomach aches and headaches, especially on school mornings, over the past 8 months. He struggles to fall asleep at night, lying awake worrying about the next day. His mother notes that he appears visibly tense, sometimes trembling, and frequently asks for reassurance that nothing bad will happen to the family. His appetite has been reduced and he reports feeling tired most of the time. On several occasions {patientName} has complained of palpitations and episodes of excessive sweating when anticipating stressful events such as a class presentation or sports competition.\n\n{patientName} lives with his parents and a younger sister in a flat in Brno. His father works long hours and his mother is a part-time nurse. The family atmosphere is caring but somewhat high-achieving. {patientName} participates in a weekly swimming class but has recently been reluctant to attend, telling his parents he is afraid of being embarrassed. He has no reported substance use, as is age-appropriate. Blood pressure measured during today's appointment was mildly elevated for his age, consistent with sustained sympathetic activation from chronic anxiety."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:3f5c2efa-df2c-4b60-927a-afec0c3bdb10",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior psychiatric hospitalizations. His parents first noticed increased worry and somatic complaints approximately 8 months ago, coinciding with a class change at school. He has a background history of allergic rhinitis, for which he was prescribed cetirizine. Notably, cetirizine — a first-generation-related antihistamine — has been associated in some paediatric reports with paradoxical CNS activation and agitation, which may have contributed to or exacerbated his anxiety symptoms over time. He also experienced a bout of recurrent tonsillitis in the past year treated with amoxicillin, to which he developed a mild urticarial reaction. {patientName} has had difficulty maintaining regular sleep, and melatonin was trialled briefly by his paediatrician for sleep onset problems; prolonged use of exogenous melatonin has been noted in some literature to subtly alter circadian HPA-axis rhythms, potentially influencing stress reactivity. He has no history of substance use and no previous surgeries. His developmental history is unremarkable; he met all milestones on time. He has no known chronic metabolic or neurological conditions. A psychological assessment was carried out at school at age 9 due to concerns about perfectionism. Concentration difficulties have been a persistent feature both at home and in the classroom."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
